[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Type founder</b></col>, <cd>one who casts or manufacture
type.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Type foundry</b></col>, <col><b>Type
foundery</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a place for the manufacture of type.</cd>
-- <col><b>Type metal</b></col>, <cd>an alloy used in making type,
stereotype plates, etc., and in backing up electrotype plates. It
consists essentially of lead and antimony, often with a little tin,
nickel, or copper.</cd> -- <col><b>Type wheel</b></col>, <cd>a wheel
having raised letters or characters on its periphery, and used in
typewriters, printing telegraphs, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Unity of
type</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>that fundamental agreement in
structure which is seen in organic beings of the same class, and is
quite independent of their habits of life.</cd>
<rj><au>Darwin.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Type</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Type
<hw>Type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Typed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Typing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To represent by a
type, model, or symbol beforehand; to prefigure.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>White (Johnson).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish an expression or copy of; to represent;
to typify.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us <qex>type</qex> them now in our own lives.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Typesetter</ent>⟦br⟧
